'''John Yeboah Zamora''' (born 23 June 2000) is a professional [[footballer]] who plays as a [[Winger (football)|winger]] for {{Italian football updater|Venezia}} club [[Venezia FC|Venezia]].<ref>{{Worldfootball.net|john-yeboah|new_id=pe450505}}</ref> Born in Germany, he plays for the [[Ecuador national football team|Ecuador national team]].

==Club career==
Yeboah began his youth career with [[Hamburg]] clubs SV Rönneburg and FC Türkiye Wilhelmsburg, before moving to youth team of [[VfL Wolfsburg]] in 2015. In February 2018, Yeboah signed his first professional contract with Wolfsburg, lasting three years until 30 June 2021.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.vfl-wolfsburg.de/en/news-detail/news-detail/detail/news/long-term-deal/ |title=Long-term deal |website=vfl-wolfsburg.de |publisher=[[VfL Wolfsburg]] |date=23 February 2018 |access-date=3 November 2018 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181103171800/https://www.vfl-wolfsburg.de/en/news-detail/news-detail/detail/news/long-term-deal/ |archive-date=3 November 2018}}</ref>

Yeboah made his professional debut for VfL Wolfsburg in the [[Bundesliga]] on 3 November 2018, coming on as a substitute in the 81st minute for [[Josip Brekalo]] in the 0–1 home loss against [[Borussia Dortmund]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.kicker.de/wolfsburg-gegen-dortmund-2018-bundesliga-4243354/analyse |title=Per Kopf: Reus besorgt den Treffer des Tages |trans-title=By head: Reus gets the strike of the day |website=[[Kicker (magazine)|Kicker]] |publisher=[[Kicker (sports magazine)|kicker-sportmagazin]] |date=3 November 2018 |access-date=3 November 2018 |language=German}}</ref>

In September 2019, Yeboah joined [[VVV-Venlo]] on a season-long loan deal.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vfl-wolfsburg.de/newsdetails/news-detail/detail/news/in-die-eredivisie/|title=In der Eredivisie|language=German|publisher=VfL Wolfsburg|date=2 September 2019|accessdate=2 September 2019}}</ref>

He was loaned to [[MSV Duisburg]] in January 2022 from his parent club, [[Willem II (football club)|Willem II]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.msv-duisburg.de/aktuelles/artikel/jung-dynamisch-und-dribbelstark-msv-leiht-john-yeboah-von-willem-ii-aus/|title="Jung, dynamisch und dribbelstark": MSV leiht John Yeboah von Willem II aus|website=msv-duisburg.de|date=12 January 2022|access-date=12 January 2022}}</ref>

On 25 June 2022, he joined Polish club [[Śląsk Wrocław]] on a three-year deal.<ref>{{cite web |title=John Yeboah piłkarzem Śląska |url=http://slaskwroclaw.pl/strona/aktualnosci/john-yeboah-pilkarzem-slaska-12850188 |publisher=[[Śląsk Wrocław]] |language=pl |date=25 June 2022}}</ref> On 15 July 2022, he made his [[Ekstraklasa]] debut, coming on as a substitute in the 0–0 Lower Silesia derby draw against [[Zagłębie Lubin]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Inauguracja na remis |url=http://slaskwroclaw.pl/strona/aktualnosci/inauguracja-na-remis-12850269 |publisher=[[Śląsk Wrocław]] |language=pl |date=15 July 2022}}</ref>

On 6 July 2023, Yeboah moved to defending Polish champions [[Raków Częstochowa]] on a three-year contract, for a fee reported to be €1.5 million.<ref>{{cite web |title=Oficjalnie: hit transferowy Rakowa! On zastąpi Iviego Lopeza |url=https://sportowefakty.wp.pl/pilka-nozna/1069541/oficjalnie-hit-transferowy-rakowa-on-zastapi-iviego-lopeza |website=sportowefakty.wp.pl |language=pl |date=6 July 2023}}</ref> After the [[2024 Copa América]] concluded, Yeboah refused to resume training in Poland, and was subsequently fined and moved to the reserve team.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Bernard |first1=Aleksander |title=Gwiazda Ekstraklasy przekroczyła kolejną granicę. "Przekreśla wszystkie lata" |url=https://www.sport.pl/pilka/7,65039,31201242,gwiazda-ekstraklasy-przekroczyla-kolejna-granice-przekresla.html |website=sport.pl |access-date=31 August 2024 |language=pl |date=5 August 2024}}</ref>

On 30 August 2024, Italian club [[Venezia FC|Venezia]] announced the signing of Yeboah on a four-year deal,<ref>{{cite web |last1=Wieczorek |first1=Bartosz |title=John Yeboah odszedł z Rakowa Częstochowa. Zagra w klubie Serie A |url=https://sport.tvp.pl/81842344/john-yeboah-odszedl-z-rakowa-czestochowa-zagra-w-klubie-serie-a |website=sport.tvp.pl |access-date=31 August 2024 |language=pl |date=30 August 2024}}</ref> for a transfer fee of over €2.5 million.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Czaplewski |first1=Jacek |title=Raków Częstochowa sprzedał Johna Yeboaha do Venezii za więcej niż podano. Mocne słowa Marka Papszuna o piłkarzu |url=https://gol24.pl/rakow-czestochowa-sprzedal-johna-yeboaha-do-venezii-za-wiecej-niz-podano-mocne-slowa-marka-papszuna-o-pilkarzu/ar/c2-18775805 |website=gol24.pl |access-date=31 August 2024 |language=pl |date=30 August 2024}}</ref>

==International career==
Born in Germany, Yeboah is eligible to play for his country of birth, as well for Ghana and Ecuador through his parents.<ref name=ECU>{{cite web |title=John Yeboah powołany do reprezentacji Ekwadoru |url=https://rakow.com/aktualnosci/john-yeboah-powolany-do-reprezentacji-ekwadoru-12752 |publisher=[[Raków Częstochowa]] |access-date=7 October 2023 |language=pl |date=7 October 2023}}</ref>

Yeboah began his youth international career with the [[Germany national under-16 football team|Germany under-16 team]], making his debut on 16 May 2016 in a friendly against [[France national under-16 football team|France]], which finished as a 1–1 away draw.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.dfb.de/datencenter/laenderspiel-2512/2015-2016/saison/2229438 |title=Frankreich U16 – Deutschland U16, 1:1, Länderspiel 2015/16 Saison |trans-title=France U16 v Germany U16, 1–1, friendly 2015–16 season |website=DFB.de |publisher=[[German Football Association]] |date=16 May 2016 |access-date=3 November 2018 |language=German}}</ref> In 2017, he was included in [[2017 UEFA European Under-17 Championship squads#Germany|Germany's squad]] for the [[2017 UEFA European Under-17 Championship]] in Croatia.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.dfb.de/news/detail/u-17-euro-wueck-nominiert-18-spieler-165896/full/1/ |title=U 17-EURO: Wück nominiert 18 Spieler |trans-title=Under-17 Euro: Wück nominates 18 players |website=DFB.de |publisher=[[German Football Association]] |date=19 April 2017 |access-date=20 August 2018 |language=German}}</ref> He scored against [[Serbia national under-17 football team|Serbia]] in the group stage, with Germany managing to reach the semi-finals before losing on penalties to [[Spain national under-17 football team|Spain]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.uefa.com/under17/season=2017/statistics/round=2000710/players/kind=goals/index.html#order=3desc |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170514034502/http://www.uefa.com/under17/season=2017/statistics/round=2000710/players/kind=goals/index.html#order=3desc |url-status=dead |archive-date=14 May 2017 |title=Statistics – Tournament phase – Player statistics – Goals |publisher=UEFA |date=19 May 2017 |access-date=20 August 2018}}</ref> Later that year, Yeboah was included in [[2017 FIFA U-17 World Cup squads#Germany|Germany's squad]] for the [[2017 FIFA U-17 World Cup]] in India. He scored against [[Colombia national under-17 football team|Colombia]] in the round of 16, with Germany later being eliminated in the quarter-finals.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.dfb.de/news/detail/wm-in-indien-wueck-nominiert-21-spieler-174365/ |title=WM in Indien: Wück nominiert 21 Spieler |trans-title=World Cup in India: Wück nominates 21 players |website=DFB.de |publisher=[[German Football Association]] |date=20 September 2017 |access-date=20 August 2018 |language=German}}</ref>

On 7 October 2023, he received his first call-up to the [[Ecuador national football team|Ecuador national team]] for the [[2026 FIFA World Cup qualification (CONMEBOL)|2026 FIFA World Cup qualifying]] matches against [[Bolivia national football team|Bolivia]] and [[Colombia national football team|Colombia]], scheduled for 12 and 16 October.<ref name=ECU/>

He featured for Ecuador during the [[2024 Copa América]] tournament played in the United States. On 4 July 2024, in a quarter-final against [[Argentina national football team|Argentina]], he provided an assist to [[Kevin Rodríguez (footballer, born 2000)|Kevin Rodríguez]] in stoppage time to tie the game at 1–1. Yeboah was one of the two Ecuadorian players to convert a penalty during an eventual shoot-out, lost by Ecuador 2–4.<ref>{{cite web |title=Quarter finals Argentina 1–1 Ecuador 07/04/2024 |url=https://copaamerica.com/en/matches/match-25-argentina-ecuador |website=copaamerica.com |access-date=5 July 2024 |language=en |date=5 July 2024}}</ref>

==Personal life ==
Yeboah was born in [[Hamburg]], [[Germany]] to a [[Ghana]]ian father and [[Ecuador]]ian mother.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Hotop |first1=Daniel |last2=Rücker |first2=Lars |url=https://www.wolfsburger-nachrichten.de/sport/vfl-wolfsburg/article215636313/Tanzt-Yeboah-bald-in-der-Bundesliga.html |title=Tanzt Yeboah bald in der Bundesliga? |trans-title=Will Yeboah be dancing in the Bundesliga soon? |work=[[Braunschweiger Zeitung]]|date=23 October 2018 |access-date=3 November 2018 |language=German |url-access=limited |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181103172721/https://www.wolfsburger-nachrichten.de/sport/vfl-wolfsburg/article215636313/Tanzt-Yeboah-bald-in-der-Bundesliga.html |archive-date=3 November 2018}}</ref>

